summary:
Tests Exception.Throws and Exception.ThrowsAsync. ThrowsAsync nicely hides away the async/await code making it easy to use. Slots into the standard MSTest namespace.

Example usage

ExceptionAssert.Throws()

ExceptionAssert.Throws<ArgumentException>(SomeMethod, "Some message");

This test will only pass if an ArgumentException with the supplied message is thrown. The message check is an optional parameter. Excluding it will mean the message is not checked.

ExceptionAssert.ThrowsAsync

ExceptionAssert.ThrowsAsync<InvalidCastException>(_controller.GetEveryone, "Cannot do it");

This tests an async controller method called GetEveryone for an InvalidCastException with the message "Cannot do it". Again the message check is optional.

To pass arguments to the method being tested wrap the call in an anonymous Func:

ExceptionAssert.Throws<ArgumentException>(() =>
{
    SomeMethod("Joe", "Bloggs", 55);
}, "Joe is an invalid first name");
